<div class="patternContent"><div class="patternTopic"> <h1><a name="Tue_Morning_Exercise_Using_glide"></a> Tue Morning Exercise - Using glideinWMS without a dedicated node </h1>
<p />
<h2 class="twikinetRoundedAttachments"><span class="twikinetHeader"><a name="Introduction"></a> Introduction </span></h2>
You have probably noticed that we use a different node for the glideinWMS exercises.<br>
This is because glideinWMS is quite a heavyweight solution; it requires properly configured Condor daemons to be running in order to work.
<p />
In this exercise, you will learn how to use a glideinWMS system without explicitly logging into a glideinWMS submit node.
<p />
<h2 class="twikinetRoundedAttachments"><span class="twikinetHeader"><a name="Remote_Condor"></a> Remote Condor </span></h2>
<p />
<a href="https://condor-wiki.cs.wisc.edu/index.cgi/wiki?p=RemoteCondor" target="_top">Remote Condor (or RCondor)</a> is a small, optional package that is distributed with Condor.
Its main function is to allow a user to use a remote Condor installation over ssh, while preserving a local look-and-feel. 
<p />
See Jeff Dost's presentation 
(<a href="http://research.cs.wisc.edu/condor/CondorWeek2012/presentations/dost-rcondor.odp" target="_top">OpenDocument</a> , <a href="http://research.cs.wisc.edu/condor/CondorWeek2012/presentations/dost-rcondor.pdf" target="_top">PDF</a>) from <a href="http://research.cs.wisc.edu/condor/CondorWeek2012/tuesday.html" target="_top">this year's Condor week</a>.
<p />
<h2 class="twikinetRoundedAttachments"><span class="twikinetHeader"><a name="Trying_Remote_Condor"></a> Trying Remote Condor </span></h2>
<p />
You can try out Remote Condor on any RedHat Linux compatible node that has sshfs installed. Follow the instructions in
Jeff's presentation 
(<a href="http://research.cs.wisc.edu/condor/CondorWeek2012/presentations/dost-rcondor.odp" target="_top">OpenDocument</a> , <a href="http://research.cs.wisc.edu/condor/CondorWeek2012/presentations/dost-rcondor.pdf" target="_top">PDF</a>).
<p />
Point Remote Condor to osg-ss-glidein.chtc.wisc.edu.
<p />
<div class="twistyPlugin twikiMakeVisibleInline">  <span id="twistyIdEducationOSGSS2012TueExRCondor1show" class="twistyTrigger twikiUnvisited twistyHidden twistyInited"><a href="#"><img src="/twiki/pub/TWiki/TWikiDocGraphics/toggleopen-small.gif" border="0" alt="" /><span class="twikiLinkLabel twikiUnvisited">Advanced</span></a> </span> <span id="twistyIdEducationOSGSS2012TueExRCondor1hide" class="twistyTrigger twikiUnvisited twistyHidden twistyInited"><a href="#"><img src="/twiki/pub/TWiki/TWikiDocGraphics/toggleclose-small.gif" border="0" alt="" /><span class="twikiLinkLabel twikiUnvisited">Hide advanced</span></a> </span>  </div><!--/twistyPlugin twikiMakeVisibleInline--> <div class="twistyPlugin"><div id="twistyIdEducationOSGSS2012TueExRCondor1toggle" class="twistyContent twikiMakeHidden twistyInited">
You will notice that you have to type you password a lot.
<p />
Try enabling <a href="http://www.debian-administration.org/articles/530" target="_top">ssh key authentication</a> (possibly without a password).
</div></div> <!--/twistyPlugin-->
<br>
<p />
<strong>Warning:</strong> If you decide to try it out on osg-ss-submit, please be aware that this will hide the "normal" Condor from you. To revert, simply comment the relevant lines from .bashrc.
<p />
<p />
<p />
-- <a href="/bin/view/Main/IgorSfiligoi" class="twikiLink">IgorSfiligoi</a> - 26 Jun 2012</div><!-- /patternTopic-->
